{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"3142674f-cda1-4fb9-af29-643b69343ad1","content":"## Using MCP Inspector with a C# stdio Server\n\nRun the MCP Inspector via `npx`:\n\n```bash\nnpx @modelcontextprotocol/inspector dotnet run --project /path/to/your/McpServer.csproj\n```\n\nThis launches a web UI (typically at `http://localhost:5173`) that:\n\n1. **Spawns your server** as a child process using stdio transport\n2. **Lists tools** — click \"Tools\" → \"List Tools\" to see registered tools\n3. **Invoke tools** — select a tool, fill in parameters, and execute it\n4. **View raw JSON-RPC** messages in the message log for debugging\n\n### Tips\n\n- If your server needs arguments, append them after `--`:\n  ```bash\n  npx @modelcontextprotocol/inspector dotnet run --project ./src/MyServer.csproj -- --my-arg value\n  ```\n- Set environment variables with `-e`:\n  ```bash\n  npx @modelcontextprotocol/inspector -e MY_VAR=foo dotnet run ...\n  ```\n- Make sure your server writes MCP JSON-RPC to **stdout** and logs/diagnostics to **stderr** — any non-protocol output on stdout will break the connection.\n- The Inspector's message pane shows the full `initialize` → `tools/list` → `tools/call` flow, which is useful for diagnosing serialization issues.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b2c1c0b8-d72c-4e5e-90d2-166f4a62f19f","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking how to use the MCP Inspector to interactively test and debug their C# MCP server that uses stdio transport. This is a general knowledge question about MCP (Model Context Protocol) tooling. I can answer this directly without needing to search files or run commands.","outputTokens":406,"requestId":"2C02:2B537A:296E41E:2DCA89E:69FD3634"},"id":"76ec1d1c-9c12-4c47-88aa-edf8a562e882","timestamp":"2026-05-08T01:02:55.100Z","parentId":"3b423baf-f50b-4739-9598-c5c78b6ab315"}
